[{"id":"VR718742","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a sphere connected to a long string attached to a ceiling. The sphere is shown in two positions: one with the string vertical and the sphere at its lowest position, and the other with the string at a small angle to the right of the vertical position and the sphere 2 centimeters above its lowest position. There is a note that the figure is not drawn to scale.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR718742.g01.svg\"/></div></div></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">A sphere is connected to a string with negligible mass, as shown, and set into simple harmonic motion by displacing it by a small angle and releasing it from rest. When the sphere is released, it is a height of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2 centimeters\"><math alttext=\"2 centimeters\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mi>cm</mi></math></span></span> above its lowest position (where the gravitational potential energy of the sphere-Earth system is defined to be zero). Shortly after release, the kinetic energy of the sphere is equal to the gravitational potential energy of the sphere-Earth system. At this instant, the speed of the sphere will be most nearly</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR718742_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"0 meters per second\"><math alttext=\"0 meters per second\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>0</mn><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mtext>m/s</mtext></math></span></span></p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"0.20 meters per second\"><math alttext=\"0.20 meters per second\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>0.20</mn><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mtext>m/s</mtext